  "eventMetadata": {
    "context_description": "Persistent inflation pressures, highlighted by April 2026 CPI rising 3.8% year-over-year—exceeding consensus and driven by energy costs—have anchored trader expectations for no change at the June 16-17 FOMC meeting, with market-implied odds at 98%. The Federal Reserve maintained its 3.50%-3.75% target range after the April gathering amid resilient labor market data and core inflation near 2.8%, shifting focus toward holding policy steady rather than easing. This consensus reflects aggregated real-money positioning on the trajectory of PCE inflation remaining above the 2% goal. A sharper-than-expected decline in May CPI or nonfarm payrolls could introduce volatility, though current forward-looking indicators suggest limited scope for such shifts before the meeting.",
    "context_requires_regen": false,
